   ART
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Arthur M. Sackler Museum, Harvard University, Cambridge,
Mass.: "The Harvest of 1830: The Barbizon Legacy" -- More
than 60 French, American and Dutch works by artists inspired
by the Barbizon School of landscape painting. The paintings,
drawings and prints -- all from the Fogg Art Museum at
Harvard -- are by such artists as Rousseau, Daubigny, Millet
and Homer. Of particular interest are a group of rarely seen
watercolors by Dutch painters Anton Mauve (van Gogh's uncle),
Jacob Maris and Jan Weissenbruch. Through Oct. 21.
                                                                                                       

   Baltimore Museum of Art: "Joel Shapiro: Tracing the
Figure" -- Twenty-five wood and bronze sculptures of the
human figure by this New York post-minimalist artist. A
concurrent exhibition, "Drawings by Sculptors," includes a
series of drawings by Mr. Shapiro as well as mid- to
late-20th-century works by Alberto Giacometti, Barry Le Va
and Mark di Suvero. Art Museum Drive, through Oct. 7. The
show then travels to the Des Moines Art Center (Nov. 17,
1990-Jan. 13, 1991) and Miami's Center for the Fine Arts
(April 6-June 2, 1991).
                                                                                                       

   Kirkpatrick Galleries, Oklahoma City, Okla.:
"Letters/Lines/Images" -- More than 100 two- and
three-dimensional art works by contemporary calligraphers
from 12 countries. 2100 N.E. 52nd St., through Oct. 2. The
show then travels to the Kemper Gallery, Kansas City Art
Institute, Kansas City, Mo. (Nov. 16-Dec. 22); the Memphis
College of Art (Jan. 7-31, 1991); and the Kresge Museum,
Michigan State University, East Lansing (Feb. 24-April 30,
1991).
                                                                                                       

   SPORT
                                                                                                       

   Michigan City (Ind.) Boat Show -- See the latest in
boating technology at this 11th annual event on Lake
Michigan. Visitors can climb aboard more than 500 1991-model
powerboats and sailboats, including cruisers, runabouts, day
sailers, water ski boats, catamarans and motor yachts. This
is also a chance to preview new marine equipment, from sails
to boating apparel and safety equipment. Washington Park,
Aug. 23-26. In Illinois, Kentucky and Michigan call (800)
634-2650. Elsewhere dial (219) 872-5055.
                                                                                                       

   FESTIVAL
                                                                                                       

   Lincoln Center's first annual Roots of American Music
Festival offers free performances by diverse artists
including blues and jazz pianist Dr. John, folk duo Robin and
Linda Williams, the Nashville Bluegrass Band and the gospel
group Voices of Thunder. Highlights include a performance of
Charles Mingus's symphonic jazz masterwork "Epitaph,"
conducted by Gunther Schuller; and the world premiere of
keyboard virtuoso David Borden's "Angels, Visions and
Apparitions." Damrosch Park Bandshell, adjacent to Lincoln
Center. Today through Aug. 27. (212) 877-2011.
                                                                                                       

   Bard Music Festival: Bard College in Annandale-on-Hudson,
in the historic Hudson River Valley area of New York, is the
site of this new festival. The inaugural season, on the theme
of "Rediscovering Brahms," offers two weeks of solo, chamber
and orchestral programs. Highlights include violinist Elmar
Oliveira's performance of the uncut version of the
"Hungarian" Violin Concerto by Joseph Joachim, a close friend
of Brahms; and a performance of Brahms's Opus 8 Piano Trio in
the seldom-heard original version of 1854. Other
participating artists include pianists Todd Crow and Sarah
Rothenberg, singers Lucy Sheldon, Jon Humphrey and William
Sharp, and the Ridge String Quartet. (914) 758-2869.
                                                                                                       

   MUSIC
                                                                                                       

   American Soviet Youth Orchestra: One hundred 17- to
24-year-old American and Soviet musicians have been brought
together by the Conservatory of Music at Oberlin College and
the Moscow State Conservatory for a seven-city U.S. tour.
Leonard Slatkin of the Saint Louis Symphony and Alexander
Lazarev of the Bolshoi Theatre Orchestra are the principal
conductors. Dates include: Highland Park, Ill. (Ravinia
Festival), Aug. 21; Orlando, Fla. (Epcot Center, Disney
World), Aug. 23 and 24; Oberlin, Ohio (Oberlin College), Aug.
25 and 26; Washington, D.C. (West Lawn of the Capitol), Aug.
28; New York, N.Y. (Winter Garden at World Financial Center),
Aug. 29; Philadelphia (Independence Mall), Aug. 30.
